<paragraph id="016C1165FF983940EBD2C250FA635C3D" blockId="54.[225,1438,1379,1804]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
This species is characterized by elliptical otoliths with blunt, but well-marked antero- and postero-dorsal angles. The rim between those two angles is almost horizontal, but may be very slightly undulated in the smaller individuals (
<figureCitation id="99E80DE0FF983940E937C298FD955EF0" box="[518,618,1451,1478]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="55.[227,270,1789,1815]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,695,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-189@55.[227,1437,695,1743]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="Fig. 18. Fish otoliths from the US middle and upper Eocene.A–F. Symmetrosulcus meyeri (Koken, 1888). A–C. Yazoo Clay, Copenhagen, Louisiana (IRSNB P10084–10086). D–F. “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (IRSNB P 10087–10089). G–K. Symmetrosulcus dockeryi sp. nov., Weches F., Wall Farm 1, Texas. G. Holotype (IRSNB P 10090). H–K. Paratypes (IRSNB P 10091–10094). L–M. “Neobythites” virginicus Müller, 1999, Piney Point F., Pamunkey River, 1 km E of Eanes property, Virginia (IRSNB P 10095–10096). N–P. Symmetrosulcus stintoni (Dante &amp; Frizzell, 1965), “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (IRSNB P 10097–10099). 1 = ventral view; 2 = inner view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484393/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 18I</figureCitation>
). The posterior portion of the otoliths forms a tapering triangle. The ventral rim is smoothly curved with its deepest part in the middle of the otolith, providing it a regular rounded appearance. The anterior part of the otolith is slightly oblique and largely blunt at its lower, most prominent part. All the margins are smooth. The otoliths are moderately thick, with both the inner and outer faces convex. The thickness may be slightly more considerable near the posterior end, which is the case in the 
<typeStatus id="DE68AFC7FF983940EA87C153FDE25D4C" box="[438,541,1632,1658]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="99E80DE0FF983940E91EC153FD625D4D" box="[559,669,1632,1659]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="55.[227,270,1789,1815]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,695,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-189@55.[227,1437,695,1743]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="Fig. 18. Fish otoliths from the US middle and upper Eocene.A–F. Symmetrosulcus meyeri (Koken, 1888). A–C. Yazoo Clay, Copenhagen, Louisiana (IRSNB P10084–10086). D–F. “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (IRSNB P 10087–10089). G–K. Symmetrosulcus dockeryi sp. nov., Weches F., Wall Farm 1, Texas. G. Holotype (IRSNB P 10090). H–K. Paratypes (IRSNB P 10091–10094). L–M. “Neobythites” virginicus Müller, 1999, Piney Point F., Pamunkey River, 1 km E of Eanes property, Virginia (IRSNB P 10095–10096). N–P. Symmetrosulcus stintoni (Dante &amp; Frizzell, 1965), “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (IRSNB P 10097–10099). 1 = ventral view; 2 = inner view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484393/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 18G</figureCitation>
). A straight sulcus occupies nearly the entire length of the inner face and is located in the central zone, but does not open to the margins of the otolith. There is a clear division into ostial and caudal parts, each fully filled by a colliculum. The cauda is about twice as long as the ostium. The cristae are clearly marked, but not ridge-like. They are almost horizontal, but the crista inferior may be slightly constricted at the collum, which is well visible in the 
<typeStatus id="DE68AFC7FF983940EF9CC1C2FAEB5C3D" box="[1197,1300,1777,1803]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="99E80DE0FF983940EE12C1C2FA705C3D" box="[1315,1423,1777,1803]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="55.[227,270,1789,1815]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,695,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-189@55.[227,1437,695,1743]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="Fig. 18. Fish otoliths from the US middle and upper Eocene.A–F. Symmetrosulcus meyeri (Koken, 1888). A–C. Yazoo Clay, Copenhagen, Louisiana (IRSNB P10084–10086). D–F. “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (IRSNB P 10087–10089). G–K. Symmetrosulcus dockeryi sp. nov., Weches F., Wall Farm 1, Texas. G. Holotype (IRSNB P 10090). H–K. Paratypes (IRSNB P 10091–10094). L–M. “Neobythites” virginicus Müller, 1999, Piney Point F., Pamunkey River, 1 km E of Eanes property, Virginia (IRSNB P 10095–10096). N–P. Symmetrosulcus stintoni (Dante &amp; Frizzell, 1965), “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (IRSNB P 10097–10099). 1 = ventral view; 2 = inner view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484393/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 18G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="49C942EEFF983940EBD2C000FC0E5338" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="016C1165FF983940EBD2C000FE815C7B" blockId="54.[227,382,1843,1869]" box="[227,382,1843,1869]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<heading id="5A24A609FF983940EBD2C000FE815C7B" bold="true" box="[227,382,1843,1869]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF983940EBD2C000FE815C7B" bold="true" box="[227,382,1843,1869]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Comparison</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF983940EBD2C050FC0E5338" blockId="54.[225,1438,1891,2063]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
The otoliths of this species can be distinguished from the co-occurring related species, 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF983940EFFBC057FED65C94" authority="(Koken, 1888)" baseAuthorityName="Koken" baseAuthorityYear="1888" class="Actinopterygii" family="Phycidae" genus="Symmetrosulcus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="meyeri">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF983940EFFBC057FAC85C4B" box="[1226,1335,1892,1918]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">S. meyeri</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF983940EE74C050FEE05C94" author="Koken" firstAuthor="Koken" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="274 - 305" refId="ref54599" refString="Koken E. 1888. Neue Untersuchungen an tertiaren Fisch-Otolithen. Zeitschrift der deutschen geologischen Gesellschaft 40: 274 - 305." type="journal article" year="1888">Koken, 1888</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF983940EA06C0BBFD1F5C94" authority="(Dante &amp; Frizzell, 1965)" baseAuthorityName="Dante &amp; Frizzell" baseAuthorityYear="1965" box="[311,736,1927,1954]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Phycidae" genus="Symmetrosulcus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="stintoni">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF983940EA06C0BBFEB95C94" box="[311,326,1928,1954]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF983940EA67C0BBFE515C97" box="[342,430,1928,1953]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">stintoni</emphasis>
(Dante &amp; 
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF983940E91EC0B4FD285C94" author="Frizzell D. L." box="[559,727,1927,1954]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="85 - 110" refId="ref53928" refString="Frizzell D. L. 1965. Otolith-based genera and lineages of fossil bonefishes (Clupeiformes, Albulidae). Senckenbergiana Lethaea 46 a: 85 - 110." type="book chapter" year="1965">Frizzell, 1965</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, “ 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF983940E9CBC0BBFCE95C97" box="[762,790,1928,1953]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">N.</emphasis>
” 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF983940E81AC0B4FC6D5C97" box="[811,914,1927,1953]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">rotundus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF983940E892C0B4FBBD5C94" author="Muller" box="[931,1090,1927,1954]" firstAuthor="Muller" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="1 - 360" refId="ref55491" refString="Muller A. 1999. Ichthyofaunen aus dem atlantischen Tertiar der USA. Leipziger Geowissenschaften 9 / 10: 1 - 360." type="journal article" year="1999">Müller, 1999</bibRefCitation>
), and “ 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF983940EFA9C0BBFB4B5C97" box="[1176,1204,1928,1953]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">N.</emphasis>
” 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF983940EFF8C0BBFAC25C97" box="[1225,1341,1928,1953]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">virginicus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FF983940EE77C0B4FEDE5CF0" author="Muller" firstAuthor="Muller" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="1 - 360" refId="ref55491" refString="Muller A. 1999. Ichthyofaunen aus dem atlantischen Tertiar der USA. Leipziger Geowissenschaften 9 / 10: 1 - 360." type="journal article" year="1999">Müller, 1999</bibRefCitation>
, by the combination of the following features: a more rectangular outline, a nearly flat dorsal rim, a more vertical anterior rim, a less extended posterior rim, and a dorsal area of similar width as the ventral one. See below for a detailed discussion on other ophidiid otoliths.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="49C942EEFF993941EBD2C61DFE045AAC" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="016C1165FF993941EBD2C61DFD115A7E" blockId="55.[227,750,302,328]" box="[227,750,302,328]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<heading id="5A24A609FF993941EBD2C61DFD115A7E" bold="true" box="[227,750,302,328]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF993941EBD2C61DFD115A7E" bold="true" box="[227,750,302,328]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Stratigraphic and geographic distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF993941EBD2C66EFE045AAC" blockId="55.[227,1436,349,410]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
Lutetian: Weches Formation, 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FF993941E972C66EFD745A41" box="[579,651,349,375]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Texas</collectingRegion>
; “lower” Lisbon Formation, 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FF993941E8D3C66EFBAF5A41" box="[994,1104,349,375]" country="United States of America" name="Alabama" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Alabama</collectingRegion>
. Bartonian: Cook Mountain Formation, 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FF993941EA5CC6B3FE085AAC" box="[365,503,384,410]" country="United States of America" name="Mississippi" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Mississippi</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
